tagged sample, with special focus on the stronger `v5a_pass` subset, to see whether first-trade-of-session weakness is persistent.\n**Finding:**\n- Both bots are alive.\n- Across all tagged trades:\n  - `FIRST`: `4` trades, `25.0%` WR, `-0.495` EV\n  - non-`FIRST`: `24` trades, `62.5%` WR, `+0.204` EV\n- Inside the stronger `v5a_pass` subset:\n  - `FIRST`: `3` trades, `0.0%` WR, `-1.000` EV\n  - non-`FIRST`: `20` trades, `70.0%` WR, `+0.354` EV\n- The four `FIRST` trades were:\n  - `2026-04-01 19:15 UTC` loss, `v5a PASS`\n  - `2026-04-03 12:15 UTC` win, `v5a BLOCK`\n  - `2026-04-06 19:05 UTC` loss, `v5a PASS`\n  - `2026-04-07 11:55 UTC` loss, `v5a PASS`\n\n**My thinking:**\nThis is the strongest evidence yet that first-trade-of-session deserves real suspicion. I still do not want to hard-code from only four total examples, but the pattern is now consistent enough to matter, especially because the stronger `v5a_pass` cases went `0 for 3`. That is exactly the kind of concentrated weakness worth keeping on the shortlist for future live promotion.\n\n**Decision:**\n-",
